Chapter 6 Lab 1

6.5.1 - Best Subset Selection

Predict Salary on the basis of various statistics with performance.

is.na() can be used to identify missing obs.

library(ISLR)

attach(Hitters)

names(Hitters)
 [1] "AtBat"     "Hits"      "HmRun"     "Runs"      "RBI"       "Walks"     "Years"     "CAtBat"   
 [9] "CHits"     "CHmRun"    "CRuns"     "CRBI"      "CWalks"    "League"    "Division"  "PutOuts"  
[17] "Assists"   "Errors"    "Salary"    "NewLeague"
dim(Hitters)
[1] 322  20
sum(is.na(Hitters$Salary))
[1] 59

na.omit can be used to remove all rows with missing values in any variable.

Hitters = na.omit(Hitters)

dim(Hitters)
[1] 263  20
sum(is.na(Hitters))
[1] 0

regsubsets(), part of the leaps library performs best subset selection by identifying the best model that contains a given number of predictors, where best is quantified using RSS.

library(leaps)

regfit.full = regsubsets(Salary ~ .,
                         Hitters,
                         nvmax = 19) # Otherwise, default is 8

reg.summary = summary(regfit.full)

Plot the statistics.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

plot(reg.summary$rss,
     xlab = "Number of Vars",
     ylab = "RSS",
     type = "l") # type = "l" is used to connect plotted points with lines

plot(reg.summary$adjr2,
     xlab = "Number of Vars",
     ylab = "Adjusted Rsq",
     type = "l") # type = "l" is used to connect plotted points with lines

which.max() can be used to identify the location of the max point of a vector.

which.max(reg.summary$adjr2)
[1] 11
plot(reg.summary$adjr2,
     xlab = "Number of Vars",
     ylab = "Adjusted Rsq",
     type = "l")

points(11,
       reg.summary$adjr2[11],
       col = "red",
       cex = 2,
       pch = 20)

plot(reg.summary$cp,
     xlab = "Number of Vars",
     ylab = "Cp",
     type = "l")

[1] 10
points(10,
       reg.summary$cp[10],
       col = "red",
       cex = 2,
       pch = 20)

plot(reg.summary$bic,

which.min(reg.summary$bic)
[1] 6

plot(regfit.full, scale="adjr2")

plot(regfit.full, scale="Cp")

plot(regfit.full, scale="bic")

6.5.3 - Choosing Among Models Using the Validation Set Approach and Cross-Validation

First, split into training set and test set.

set.seed(647)

train = sample(c(TRUE, FALSE),
               nrow(Hitters),
               rep = TRUE)

test = (!train)

length(train)
[1] 263
test[1:10]
 [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE  TRUE FALSE

Theres no predict() for regsubsets(). Create our own.

predict.regsubsets = function(object, newdata, id, ...) {
  form = as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat = model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi = coef(object, id = id)
  xvars = names(coefi)
  mat[, xvars] %*% coefi
}

In the jth fold, the elements of folds that equal j are in the test set, and the remainder are in the training set.

We make our predictions for each model size, compute the test errors and store them in cv.errors.

for (j in 1:k) {
  best.fit = regsubsets(Salary ~ .,
                        Hitters[folds != j,],
                        nvmax = 19) # Anything that doesn't equal to j are in the training set
  
  for (i in 1:19) {
    pred = predict.regsubsets(best.fit,
                              Hitters[folds == j, ],
                              id = i)
    cv.errors[j, i] = mean((Hitters$Salary[folds == j] - pred) ^ 2)
  }
}
